Fix Bug 1 (message duplication) — Layer 1: Add a streaming guard to the sync_update EventSource listener in `apps/client/src/layers/features/chat/model/use-chat-session.ts`.

## Problem

The `sync_update` handler at lines 270-273 calls `queryClient.invalidateQueries()` unconditionally. When a tool call completes, the SDK writes to the transcript, which fires `sync_update`. At the same time, the `done` event arrives and transitions status from `streaming` → `idle`. The history refetch triggered by `sync_update` races with the `done` transition: the seed effect (lines 210-217) runs with `isStreaming === false` and appends `history.slice(currentMessages.length)` — but `currentMessages` already contains the streamed text, so the same content is appended again.

## Fix

Use `statusRef` (already at line 134, kept in sync via a synchronous `useEffect` on every render) to read the current streaming status inside the listener closure. Closures capture values at creation time; `statusRef.current` gives the live value.

**File:** `apps/client/src/layers/features/chat/model/use-chat-session.ts`
**Lines to change:** 270-273

```typescript
// BEFORE:
eventSource.addEventListener('sync_update', () => {
  queryClient.invalidateQueries({ queryKey: ['messages', sessionId, selectedCwdRef.current] });
  queryClient.invalidateQueries({ queryKey: ['tasks', sessionId, selectedCwdRef.current] });
});

// AFTER:
eventSource.addEventListener('sync_update', () => {
  // Skip invalidation during active streaming — relay_message events already update
  // local state. The refetch would race with the done event and cause duplicates.
  if (statusRef.current === 'streaming') return;
  queryClient.invalidateQueries({ queryKey: ['messages', sessionId, selectedCwdRef.current] });
  queryClient.invalidateQueries({ queryKey: ['tasks', sessionId, selectedCwdRef.current] });
});
```

## Key Invariant

`statusRef` is already maintained at line 134-137:
```typescript
const statusRef = useRef(status);
useEffect(() => {
  statusRef.current = status;
});
```
This synchronous effect (no dependency array means it runs after every render) ensures `statusRef.current` always reflects the latest `status` value. The guard `statusRef.current === 'streaming'` is safe to use inside the closure.

## Invariant Preserved

When `sync_update` fires after the `done` event transitions status to `'idle'`, `statusRef.current` will be `'idle'`, the guard will not return early, and `invalidateQueries()` will fire — post-stream history sync is unaffected.

## Acceptance Criteria

- The `sync_update` listener body is NOT reached when `statusRef.current === 'streaming'`
- The `sync_update` listener body IS reached when `statusRef.current === 'idle'`
- No new state, refs, or imports are required — `statusRef` is already in scope
- The change is exactly 1 inserted line (`if (statusRef.current === 'streaming') return;`) plus a code comment
- All existing relay tests in `apps/client/src/layers/features/chat/model/__tests__/use-chat-session-relay.test.ts` continue to pass

Fix Bug 1 (message duplication) — Layer 2: Replace the index-based history merge in the seed effect with an ID-set filter in `apps/client/src/layers/features/chat/model/use-chat-session.ts`.

## Problem

The current seed effect (lines 210-217) uses `history.slice(currentMessages.length)` to find new messages to append. This assumes no overlap between local streaming state and server history — an assumption that fails under any timing race. If the history refetch completes during the streaming→idle transition window, `currentMessages.length` may not accurately reflect which messages are already rendered locally, causing already-streamed content to be appended again.

## Fix

Replace the slice-based merge with an ID-set filter. `HistoryMessage.id` is a stable UUID present on all history messages (confirmed by `mapHistoryMessage()` at line 69: `id: m.id`).

**File:** `apps/client/src/layers/features/chat/model/use-chat-session.ts`
**Lines to change:** 210-217

```typescript
// BEFORE:
if (historySeededRef.current && !isStreaming) {
  const currentMessages = messagesRef.current;
  const newMessages = history.slice(currentMessages.length);

  if (newMessages.length > 0) {
    setMessages((prev) => [...prev, ...newMessages.map(mapHistoryMessage)]);
  }
}

// AFTER:
if (historySeededRef.current && !isStreaming) {
  const currentIds = new Set(messagesRef.current.map((m) => m.id));
  const newMessages = history.filter((m) => !currentIds.has(m.id));

  if (newMessages.length > 0) {
    setMessages((prev) => [...prev, ...newMessages.map(mapHistoryMessage)]);
  }
}
```

## Why Both Layers Are Needed

Task 1.1 eliminates the unnecessary refetch during streaming (the root cause). This task eliminates duplicate rendering even if a refetch does complete during the streaming→idle transition window — defense in depth against any timing race, not just the `sync_update` race.

## Performance Notes

`new Set(messagesRef.current.map(...))` runs on every `historyQuery.data` change. With typical session message counts (< 200 per session), this is O(n) and negligible. No memoization is needed.

## Acceptance Criteria

- The seed effect uses `currentIds` Set + `.filter()` instead of `.slice(currentMessages.length)`
- Messages already present in local state (by `id`) are never appended from history
- New messages (IDs not in local state) are still correctly appended
- The `messagesRef` ref is already maintained by the hook — no new refs required
- All existing relay and legacy tests continue to pass
- Manually verify: if `history = [A, B, C]` and `messagesRef.current = [A, B]`, only `C` is appended

Fix Bug 2 (503 storm) — Layer 1: Extend the `refetchInterval` guard in `historyQuery` to also return `false` when Relay mode is active in `apps/client/src/layers/features/chat/model/use-chat-session.ts`.

## Problem

In Relay mode, `sync_update` SSE events from the persistent EventSource already drive all history invalidation via `queryClient.invalidateQueries()`. The `refetchInterval` polling (every 3 seconds on an active tab) is entirely redundant. Each poll hits `GET /api/sessions/:id/messages`, which must read the SDK JSONL transcript file. Under Relay-mode load, these repeated reads contribute to the 503 storm.

## Fix

Add `|| relayEnabled` to the existing `isStreaming` guard so the interval returns `false` for the entire Relay session — both during and between streaming.

`relayEnabled` is already in scope at line 85: `const relayEnabled = useRelayEnabled();`

**File:** `apps/client/src/layers/features/chat/model/use-chat-session.ts`
**Lines to change:** 184-189

```typescript
// BEFORE:
refetchInterval: () => {
  if (isStreaming) return false;
  return isTabVisible
    ? QUERY_TIMING.ACTIVE_TAB_REFETCH_MS
    : QUERY_TIMING.BACKGROUND_TAB_REFETCH_MS;
},

// AFTER:
refetchInterval: () => {
  // In Relay mode, sync_update SSE events drive invalidation — polling is redundant
  if (isStreaming || relayEnabled) return false;
  return isTabVisible
    ? QUERY_TIMING.ACTIVE_TAB_REFETCH_MS
    : QUERY_TIMING.BACKGROUND_TAB_REFETCH_MS;
},
```

## TanStack Query v5 Constraint — Critical

Use `refetchInterval: () => false` — NOT `enabled: false`. In TanStack Query v5, setting `enabled: false` causes the query to silently ignore `invalidateQueries()` and `refetchQueries()` calls. This would break post-stream history sync (when `sync_update` fires after streaming completes, the invalidation would have no effect). The function form of `refetchInterval` returning `false` correctly disables polling while preserving `invalidateQueries()` reactivity.

Reference: https://tanstack.com/query/v5/docs/framework/react/guides/disabling-queries — "When enabled is false, the query will ignore query client invalidateQueries and refetchQueries calls"

## EventSource Loss Coverage

If the EventSource disconnects in Relay mode, it auto-reconnects (browser standard behavior). The staleness detector (lines 220-242) provides a 15-second fallback: if no events arrive for 15s, it polls `transport.getSession()` and invalidates history on recovery. This covers the edge case where `sync_update` events are missed during a reconnect window.

## Acceptance Criteria

- When `relayEnabled` is `true`, `refetchInterval` returns `false` regardless of `isStreaming` value
- When `relayEnabled` is `false`, the original polling behavior is preserved (returns interval based on tab visibility)
- `invalidateQueries()` calls still trigger refetches in Relay mode (proving `enabled: false` was NOT used)
- No new imports required — `relayEnabled` and `useRelayEnabled` are already in scope
- All existing relay and legacy tests continue to pass

Fix Bug 2 (503 storm) — Layer 2: Wrap the `GET /:id/messages` handler body in try/catch with `next(err)` in `apps/server/src/routes/sessions.ts`.

## Problem

Express 4 does not automatically forward unhandled async rejections in route handlers to error middleware. When `runtime.getMessageHistory()` or `runtime.getSessionETag()` throws (e.g., due to transcript I/O contention, session write lock, or Relay-mode state conflict), the request hangs with no response. A proxy timeout then returns a 503 to the client. This is a latent correctness bug that surfaces under Relay-mode polling volume.

Note: Express 5 fixes this by automatically calling `next(err)` for unhandled promise rejections in async routes. DorkOS uses Express 4.

## Fix

Add `next` parameter to the route handler signature and wrap the async body in try/catch.

**File:** `apps/server/src/routes/sessions.ts`
**Lines to change:** 116-139 (GET `/:id/messages` handler)

```typescript
// BEFORE:
router.get('/:id/messages', async (req, res) => {
  const sessionId = parseSessionId(req.params.id);
  if (!sessionId) return sendError(res, 400, 'Invalid session ID', 'INVALID_SESSION_ID');

  const cwdParam = (req.query.cwd as string) || undefined;
  if (!(await assertBoundary(cwdParam, res))) return;
  const cwd = cwdParam || vaultRoot;

  const runtime = runtimeRegistry.getDefault();
  const internalSessionId = runtime.getInternalSessionId(sessionId) ?? sessionId;

  const etag = await runtime.getSessionETag(cwd, internalSessionId);
  if (etag) {
    res.setHeader('ETag', etag);
    if (req.headers['if-none-match'] === etag) {
      return res.status(304).end();
    }
  }

  const messages = await runtime.getMessageHistory(cwd, internalSessionId);
  res.json({ messages });
});

// AFTER:
router.get('/:id/messages', async (req, res, next) => {
  const sessionId = parseSessionId(req.params.id);
  if (!sessionId) return sendError(res, 400, 'Invalid session ID', 'INVALID_SESSION_ID');

  const cwdParam = (req.query.cwd as string) || undefined;
  if (!(await assertBoundary(cwdParam, res))) return;
  const cwd = cwdParam || vaultRoot;

  try {
    const runtime = runtimeRegistry.getDefault();
    const internalSessionId = runtime.getInternalSessionId(sessionId) ?? sessionId;

    const etag = await runtime.getSessionETag(cwd, internalSessionId);
    if (etag) {
      res.setHeader('ETag', etag);
      if (req.headers['if-none-match'] === etag) {
        return res.status(304).end();
      }
    }

    const messages = await runtime.getMessageHistory(cwd, internalSessionId);
    res.json({ messages });
  } catch (err) {
    next(err);
  }
});
```

## Scope

This fix applies to all callers, not just Relay-mode polling. Any future error condition that causes `getMessageHistory` or `getSessionETag` to throw will return a proper 500 response immediately instead of hanging.

Note: The `assertBoundary(cwdParam, res)` check remains OUTSIDE the try/catch block intentionally — it handles its own error response internally and returns `false` on failure. Moving it inside the try/catch would not break behavior but would be unnecessary.

## Acceptance Criteria

- The route handler signature includes `next` as the third parameter
- `runtime.getDefault()`, `getSessionETag()`, and `getMessageHistory()` calls are all inside the try/catch
- When `getMessageHistory` throws, `next(err)` is called and Express error middleware returns 500
- When `getSessionETag` throws, `next(err)` is called and Express error middleware returns 500
- The 304 ETag path continues to work correctly
- All existing `sessions.test.ts` success-path tests pass unchanged

